related_questions.question: What kind of alcohol is sake?
related_questions.snippet: Many people refer to sake as “Japanese rice wine,” but it doesn't actually fall into the category of liquor, beer or wine. It features a bit of all three — it has one fermented ingredient like wine, is brewed like beer, and has higher alcohol content like liquor.

buttons.subtitle: What Does Sake Taste Like?
buttons.title: What Does Sake Taste Like? – Tippsy Sake Blog}
buttons.snippet: A vast amount of sake possesses fruity aromas and flavors, such as melon, apple, pear and more. Floral tones are also common. This has a lot to do with the kind of yeast used. A large portion of fruity and floral sake are ginjo and daiginjo.

buttons.subtitle: What Flavor Is Sake?
buttons.title: INTRODUCTION to SAKE
buttons.snippet: Even though rice has a rather bland flavor, sake, particularly Ginjo-shu, has fruity flavors similar to apples, bananas, and various fruits.
snippet_highlighted_words: fruity flavors similar to apples, bananas, and various fruits

buttons.subtitle: How Do You Drink Sake
buttons.title: Sake 101—The Ultimate Guide to Japanese Sake | Guide | Travel Japan
buttons.snippet: How is sake served? Sake can be served chilled, warmed or at room temperature. Some types, like ginjo, are preferred cool, while junmai is often enjoyed at room temperature or warmed. Each individual sake has its own temperature that best brings out the flavors, and personal preference is extremely important as well.
snippet_highlighted_words: chilled, warmed or at room temperature

buttons.title: Is Sake Wine or Liquor | Quick Facts on Sake
buttons.snippet: Though sake is often referred to as a “Japanese rice wine,” it actually doesn't fall into the categories of wine, beer or spirits. Rather, sake takes on its own drink category as it involves a unique production method.

buttons.subtitle: Is Sake Sweet Or Dry
buttons.title: What Does Sake Taste Like? | Japan Sake and Shochu Makers Association
buttons.snippet: Sake tastes sweet when the sugar content is high and the acidity is low. Sake's relatively low acidity compared to semi-sweet wine gives it a sweeter impression. However, acidity provided by succinic acid and lactic acid can mask the sweet taste even with relatively high sugar content.
snippet_highlighted_words: Sake tastes sweet when the sugar content is high and the acidity is low

buttons.snippet: Traditionally, sake is best enjoyed during the appetizer phase of the meal, or during tapas-style dining called 'izakaya. ' You may even enjoy sipping sake with light sushi options such as sashimi or nigiri. Different sakes can bring out the flavors in the appetizers and make the meal even more enjoyable and memorable.
